<assessment id="u4_m1_confintprop3_tutor1">
    <title>Tutor</title>
    <question id="q1">
        <body>What sample size of U.S. adults do you need, if you would like to estimate the
            proportion of
            U<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102155-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>S<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102156-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>
            adults who are "pro-choice" with a 2.5% margin of error (at the 95% level)?</body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">40</choice>
            <choice value="B">16</choice>
            <choice value="C"
                >1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102213-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>000</choice>
            <choice value="D"
                >1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102216-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>600</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A">
                <feedback>Incorrect. It seems like your mistake is that you are
                    forgetting to square the margin of error in the denominator. Try
                again.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B">
                <feedback>Incorrect. It seems like you converted 2.5% to .25, and used
                    that as m. Note that 2.5%<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102227-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102227-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>.025. </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="C">
                <feedback>Incorrect. Recall that the sample size needed for a desired
                    margin of error m (at the 95%) level is found (conservatively) by n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102237-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102238-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102238-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>/<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102239-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>m<sup>2</sup>. </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="D" score="10">
                <feedback>Good
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102246-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102245-0500" content="J"?>ob!
                    Indeed<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102250-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    the sample size needed for a margin of error of 2.5% (at the 95% level) is 1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102258-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>/<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102258-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>(.025)<sup>2</sup> =
                    1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102302-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>600.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
    <question id="q2">
        <body>Your answer to the above question indicates that if you take a sample of that size, the sample
            proportion of adults who are pro-choice is:</body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">more than 2.5% away from the proportion who are pro-choice among all
                U<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102326-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>S<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102326-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>
                adults.</choice>
            <choice value="B">within 2.5% of the proportion who are pro-choice among all
                U<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102331-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>S<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102331-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>
                adults.</choice>
            <choice value="C">exactly equal to the proportion who are pro-choice among all
                U<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102610-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>S<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102611-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>
                adults.</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A">
                <feedback>Incorrect. The margin of error m means that the sample
                    proportion will be no more than m units away from the known population
                    proportion it estimates. </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B" score="10">
                <feedback>Good
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102342-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102342-0500" content="J"?>ob<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102346-0500"?>!<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102344-0500" content="."?>
                    Indeed<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102350-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    a sample size of n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102353-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102354-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102355-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>600
                    guarantees that m<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102359-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102359-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>2.5%, which means that the sample proportion that we
                    get<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102406-0500" content="s"?>
                    will be no more than 2.5% away from the population proportion it estimates (at
                    the 95% level).</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="C">
                <feedback>Incorrect. There is no sample size large enough
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102421-0500"?>to<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102422-0500" content="that could"?>
                    guarantee<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102439-0500" content=" something like"?>
                    that<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102445-0500"?>
                    result<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102447-0500" content="!"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102448-0500"?>.
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102721-0500" comment="Addition OK?"?>In
                    order to obtain that result, we would have to collect data from every single
                    U.S. adult, not just a sample of that
                    population.<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_end?> The best we can do is determine
                    a sample size that will guarantee that the sample proportion will be within a
                    certain margin of error of the population proportion it estimates. Review the
                    material on this page again.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
    <question id="q3">
        <body><p>If you were to use a random sample of size n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102752-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102753-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>640
                U<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102756-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>S<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102756-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?>
                adults (instead of what you found in question 1), what would the margin of error
                roughly be?</p></body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">4%</choice>
            <choice value="B">.156%</choice>
            <choice value="C">3%</choice>
            <choice value="D">5%</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A" score="10">
                <feedback>Good
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102808-0500"?>j<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102808-0500" content="J"?>ob!
                    Indeed, using the conservative approach, the margin of error would roughly be 1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102815-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>/<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102815-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>sqrt(640) = .0395, which equals approximately .04 </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B">
                <feedback>Incorrect. It seems like you forgot to take the square root
                    in the denominator. </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="C">
                <feedback>Incorrect. Recall that (conservatively) m<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102847-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102847-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102848-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>/<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102851-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>sqrt(n). </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="D">
                <feedback>Incorrect. Recall that (conservatively) m<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102858-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102859-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102900-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>/<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T102900-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>sqrt(n). </feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
</assessment>
